Hub impact confidently.” That directly undermines the Bull’s claim that LNG tightening is clearly “underpriced” on the information given, whereas the Bear’s supply evidence is already expressed in concrete volumetric terms.\n\nOn storage and near-term signals, the Bull leans on the five-year deficit compressing to 17 Bcf below average, but the Inventory analyst explicitly warns this is partly seasonal and likely already priced; using it as a bullish reversal proof conflicts with the report’s own critique. The Bear also points out the 141 Bcf year-on-year storage surplus as a durable bearish anchor (even if its incremental “news” value is diminishing). The technical/context data are also more consistent with the Bear’s caution: market regime is TRENDING, price is well below the 200-day SMA, and the 5-day trend is meaningfully negative, while the 24h change is essentially flat—there is no clear confirmation that a bullish catalyst is being repriced upward right now.\n\nOn positioning/short squeeze, the Bull cites a large net short and moderate implied vol with upside skew, but the Sentiment report is explicit that COT data is not recent (no last 24–48h update). The Bear’s critique that squeeze fuel may be partly spent after a multi-day selloff is plausible, and the evidence provided cannot confirm an imminent squeeze.\n\nPutting it together under symmetric standards: the Bull does establish that LNG demand growth is real and structural, but the packet does not quantify it in a way that proves it dominates the equally well-evidenced supply growth. The Bear provides more directly comparable, volumetric supply evidence plus corroborating market behavior (trend/regime, weak immediate reaction), making the bearish case better grounded in current data. That said, because multiple reports are neutral and explicitly highlight missing variables (weather, industrial demand, storage context, real-time rigs), the bearish call is not “proven,” only more plausible than the bullish 